the commentators have, however, doubted whether Horace could have ventured to speak so freer, as in the concluding lines, of av Roman matron of rank so illustrious as Terentia, and would therefore assume Licymnia to have been rather the mistress than the wife of Maecenas. This supposition is incompatible with the description of Licymnia Joining in the festivals of Diana 3 and probably Horace sufficiently preserved such respect to the wife of his patron as the manners of the time required by substituting a feigned name for her own.
